    "summary": "The Sino-French War (1884–85) was a conflict between Qing China and the French Republic over control of northern Vietnam (Tonkin), which China regarded as a tributary state. The war ended without a formal peace treaty — technically it was never officially declared — but resulted in French control of Indochina and was part of the broader pattern of Western encroachment on Chinese influence in Asia.\n\nFrance had been gradually extending its colonial presence in Southeast Asia: Cochinchina (southern Vietnam) had been seized in 1862, and France established a protectorate over Cambodia in 1863. French expansion into northern Vietnam brought it into conflict with China's claim to suzerainty over the region and with the Black Flag Army, an irregular Chinese force nominally aligned with Chinese interests. When negotiations broke down, full-scale fighting began.\n\nThe war produced mixed military results. French naval forces destroyed the Chinese Fujian (Foochow) Fleet in a surprise attack in August 1884, demonstrating once again the vulnerability of Chinese naval forces to Western attack. However, Chinese land forces under Liu Yongfu's Black Flag Army and regular Yunnan troops performed more creditably, and the Chinese victory at the Battle of Bang Bo (Langson) in March 1885 caused a political crisis in France, bringing down the government of Prime Minister Jules Ferry.\n\nDespite this setback, France was in a stronger overall position and the subsequent Treaty of Tientsin (1885) confirmed French control over Tonkin and established France's Indochina colony. China abandoned its claim to suzerainty over Vietnam — a significant retreat from its traditional sphere of influence in mainland Southeast Asia. The war contributed to the broader Chinese debate about modernization and contributed indirectly to the [[event:2625|Self-Strengthening Movement's]] efforts to rebuild Chinese naval and military power.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sino-French_War",
